title: MountainStar Healthcare prep star athletes of Week 9
text:
A quick look at the Deseret News' Preps of the Week.
“ I was just really impressed with not just her playing but her personality, leadership on the team and example to everybody.”
Alta tennis coach Camille Baird said of Emilee Astle
Emilee Astle, Alta, tennis
Emilee Astle is a freshman from Alta High School. She is also the 4A first singles champion in girls’ tennis.
“I knew coming in she was going to be a good player,” Alta’s head coach Camille Baird said. “I was just really impressed with not just her playing but her personality, leadership on the team and example to everybody.”
Astle has been playing tennis since the age of 10. It was her piano teacher who got her into playing tennis.
“I just started taking lessons from her daughters that played tennis,” Astle said.
Ryker Osborne , Juab, football
With about three minutes left in Juab's back-and-forth, high-scoring affair with Union, Juab quarterback Ryker Osborne was faced with a fourth-and-9 situation from Union's 33-yard line with his team trailing 48-42.
The junior quarterback had to make a play and he responded with a well-placed strike to receiver Nolan Nielsen for a 49-48 victory.
"We needed a big play, so we made the call and he was able to hit Nolan for the win," said Juab coach Mike Bowring . "It was a great play for us to win an important game against Union."
For the game Osborne went 14 of 24 through the air for 244 yards and four touchdowns. He also scored on a 5-yard touchdown run late in the game to keep the game close and to help set up his late-minute touchdown pass.
"He arguably played his best game yet for us," Bowring said. "He's really learning to go to his second read and it's exciting to see him develop and have the kind of game he did for us last week."
Other stars
Rhett Rasmussen, Corner Canyon, golf
The Corner Canyon senior and BYU commit shot 68 and 65 at the state tournament to take medalist honors and cap his illustrious career with a win. Rasmussen also won the Salt Lake City Open and took second in the City Amateur.
Holly Daugirda , Skyline, soccer
This electrifying scorer and unswerving leader has been up to her typical dominant ways at just the right time.
The senior forward and University of Utah commit came up huge with two points in Skyline’s 4A quarterfinal matchup against Woods Cross Thursday as she scored one goal and buried a key PK en route to a thrilling 1-1 (4-3 SO) victory and semifinal berth.
Daugirda, who is tied for first in 4A in goals scored with a career-best 26, has recorded eight multiple-goal games and dished out 13 assists in 18 games this season and was one of 24 players to train with the U.S. Under-19 Women’s National Team earlier this month.
“She’s an amazing player. She makes everyone around her a better player. She always has a great attitude and is a great leader for our team,” Skyline head coach Yamil Castillo said.
Landon Chappell , Wayne, baseball
When Wayne's Landon Chappell got the call as his team's starting pitcher in the 1A state championship game against Tabiona, the junior seized the moment.
"It's a rush," Chappell said of getting the starting call. "It's something you've been working toward since you were 3 years old — it's what you've practiced all your life for."
Chappell pitched three innings on Saturday, helping secure an early lead before rotating to play catcher. Chappell also helped out from the plate with an RBI single and four walks in his five plate appearances.
